2026-05-20  ProductSpec § Reorganization approved (drafted 2026-05-19; reshaped per owner feedback 2026-05-20). Four concepts canonical: Reparent, Promotion, Sibling reorder, Sibling sort. Drag drop-band semantics within a row (center → reparent, edges → reorder above/below). Sort-mode preference cascades User → Initiative → List → parent task with "inherit" as the implicit default. Sibling reorder always flips parent to manual mode. Cross-Initiative reorganization moved to Optional / Future (not currently supported).
2026-05-20  M02 Arc 3 renumbered to accommodate the § Reorganization rollout. Eight new items inserted as 13–20: Sort-mode storage + inheritance, sibling sort engine, sort menu in Details panel, resort-all-posterity helper, drag drop-band semantics, top + bottom root-level overlay drop zones, new-task placement defaults, sibling reorder mode flip. Per the owner's "insert" semantics, testing renumbered from 11 → 21 (testing stays last item); manual_progress on branches renumbered 12 → 11; vertical-only drag renumbered 13 → 12. Prior commit references to item 11 (testing) and items 12 / 13 refer to the state at time of commit; current state is the source of truth going forward. Item count 13 → 21; m02-ux-buildout rollup updated.
2026-05-20  M02 Arc 3 reordered: testing findings now sit adjacent to testing. The Reorganization items (was 13–20) moved to 11–18; the in-browser-testing findings (was 11 manual_progress, 12 vertical-only drag) moved to 19–20; testing stays at 21. Logic: findings surface FROM testing, so they belong as the last feature group before the testing item, not as the first items after the original ten. Same commit strips meta-journaling from the arc doc body — dates, "added on," "renumbered from," "was item X," "approved on" notes all moved out of the doc; the doc reads like a spec, CHANGELOG carries the history.
2026-06-03  Fix: dark-mode link contrast. Four text-style links/buttons used hover:text-zinc-800 with no dark variant, going dark-on-dark on hover; the two auth links ("Need an account? Register", "Have an account? Log in") were also dark-blind at base (text-zinc-500 only). Added dark:text-zinc-400 dark:hover:text-zinc-200 to the auth links and dark:hover:text-white to the two Details-panel Cancel buttons (cancel-member, cancel-add-task).
2026-06-04  Mobile theme toggle. The three-button System/Light/Dark group is cramped on phones; below the sm breakpoint it now collapses to a single icon showing the current theme that cycles System → Light → Dark on tap (new ThemeCycle hook — mirrors the desktop group's phx:set-theme client dispatch + set_theme server persistence; phx-update="ignore" so the hook owns the icon). Desktop keeps the explicit three-button group (hidden sm:inline-flex).
2026-06-05  Mobile header pass. (1) The single-icon cycling theme toggle is now login-screens-only (theme_toggle :auto variant); the logged-in nav collapses into a hamburger (JS-free details/summary, works on dead views) holding Initiatives, name, a full theme group (:group variant), and Log out — desktop nav unchanged. (2) Initiative show page: "← All initiatives" and "Your role" now share one row; the title row (grove icon + name) is dedicated, with the New List button inline on desktop but moved below the description on mobile.
2026-06-05  Delete-initiative feature (a CRUD gap — you could create an initiative but never delete one). Owner-only "Delete initiative" action at the bottom of the initiative Details pane, with a confirm naming the initiative. Initiatives.delete_initiative/1 leans on the DB FK cascades (initiative_members / tasks / activity_events all ON DELETE CASCADE; tasks in turn cascade their comments + activity) so a single Repo.delete cleans everything up. Redirects to /initiatives after. Handler gated on can_admin? (owner).
2026-06-05  Fix two completion glitches. (1) Unchecking a completed branch left progress at 100%: maybe_set_done_progress snapped manual_progress to 100 on done but never reset it on reopen — only the leaf toggle path passed 0 explicitly, so the cascade (branch uncheck) left descendants pinned at 100. Made the snap symmetric (done->100, reopen->0) so every path resets. Regression test added. (2) Reordering tasks that flip completion sometimes left checkboxes stale: task <li> rows had no stable DOM id, so morphdom matched by position and could patch the wrong row on a reorder. Added id={"task-#{id}"}.
2026-06-08  Fix: a legacy sort_mode crashed moves. A task carried sort_mode "status" — an earlier name for what's now "completion" (both rank by task status). DoIt.Tasks.Sort.mode_compare/3 has no clause for "status", so any move that triggered a resort of that branch (here: dropping a task into it) raised FunctionClauseError inside the move transaction — which runs within preview_move — rolling the whole thing back and terminating the LiveView. Symptom looked like a bad drag plan ("task didn't stay, didn't save"), but the client was pushing correct params; the server blew up on the resort. Durable fix: Sort.apply/3 now treats any mode outside the known set (alphabetical/completion/computed_progress/priority/created/updated) as manual — preserve order, never crash — so a stray sort_mode can't take down a move or resort again; regression test added (a "status" and a "bogus" mode both degrade to no-op). Data cleanup: migration normalize_legacy_status_sort_mode maps the remaining "status" row → "completion". Surfaced during in-browser drag testing.
2026-06-08  Fix: marking a branch done left its parent at 100% progress with an unchecked box. cascade_status reconciled ancestors only on the "open" (uncheck) direction — the "done" direction cascaded to descendants and recomputed the parent's progress (→100) but never walked up to auto-check a now-fully-done ancestor. The leaf path (toggle_complete) already did this; the branch cascade missed it. Made the up-walk symmetric: cascading to "done" now calls check_completed_ancestors on the parent, mirroring the uncheck_done_ancestors call on reopen. Regression test added. Surfaced during §8.7 in-browser testing.
2026-06-08  Fix: task deletion never persisted (+ red Delete button, Del shortcut). delete_task recorded its "deleted" activity event AFTER Repo.delete, with task_id pointing at the just-deleted task; activity_events.task_id is references(:tasks, on_delete: :delete_all), null: false, so the insert raised an FK violation and rolled the whole delete back — every task delete silently aborted (the "long redraw" was the unchanged subtree re-rendering after the abort). The deletion is now logged on the surviving parent's timeline instead (kind "child_deleted", via a new record_event_for/5 helper), so the delete commits and cascades the subtree; regression test added. Same pass: the Details-pane Delete control became a red button (trash icon) instead of a text link, and a Del keyboard shortcut deletes the selected task (clicks the button so the confirm dialog still gates it).
2026-06-09  Fix: Alt+arrow sibling reorder pinked the whole ancestor chain. The keyboard reorg path marked row + savingAncestors for every Alt+arrow, but sibling order doesn't roll up — only dedent/indent (reparenting) recompute ancestor progress. Alt+up/down now pinks just the two swapped rows, plus the immediate parent only when the reorder flips it from auto-sort to manual sort_mode (an already-manual parent doesn't change); the drag path got the same manual-mode gate. The resolved sort mode is exposed as data-sort-mode on each children <ul> (and #task-tree) so the client can tell. Same pass: impossible reorgs (Alt+up on a first child, Alt+down on a last child, Alt+left at top level, Alt+right with no previous sibling) now play a short WebAudio "bonk" and skip the server round-trip instead of pinking and no-op'ing (.03.07.02.12). Surfaced during §8.9 in-browser testing.
2026-06-09  Fix: move paths over-pinked, and confirmed writes lost their hue. Three §8.9/§8.8 findings in one pass. (1) Indent/dedent (keyboard) and cross-parent drag pinked entire ancestor chains; ancestor progress updates are value-dependent, so move paths now pink only rows with certain writes: the moved row, the swapped sibling (reorder), and the parent when a reorder flips it from auto-sort to manual (the resolved mode is exposed as data-sort-mode on each children <ul> / #task-tree so the client can tell). (2) When an action raised a confirm modal, the re-render stripped the interaction-time pink and Proceed committed the write with no hue at all; pink now means "maybe write" — while a modal is pending, the rows its write would touch (cascade subtree + ancestors, the doomed subtree on a delete, moved row + flipped tasks on a move/create) hold the hue, rendered server-side via a pending_saving_ids assign so it survives re-renders. Cancel unpinks; Proceed keeps the hue through the write. preview_create/preview_move now return flip ids alongside titles, and Tasks gained public subtree_ids/1 + ancestor_ids/1. (3) aria-pressed on the completion toggle rendered as a presence-only attribute (invalid ARIA — it must be literal "true"/"false"); now stringified. Caught by the first Playwright e2e smoke run.
2026-06-09  Fix: keyboard moves bypassed the completion-flip confirm. do_kbd_move called Tasks.move_task directly, so an Alt+arrow indent/dedent that would flip ancestor completion committed silently while the identical drag raised the styled modal. Keyboard moves now go through the same preview_move -> confirm path: scenario nil commits, a flip raises the modal (with the maybe-write hue) unless the "completion changes" class is suppressed. Regression tests added (modal gates the move; Cancel leaves the tree untouched). Found while wiring the §8.9 finding fixes.
2026-06-09  Perf: collapsed the N+1s behind sluggish confirm modals. Measured on the dev tree (28 tasks, warm): subtree_ids 208ms -> 30ms, count_descendants 152ms -> 10ms, and the per-render sort-mode cost eliminated. Two changes: (1) list_descendants is now a single recursive CTE instead of one query per node (structs get their source meta reset from the CTE name so cascade updates still target tasks) — all callers benefit: cascade status writes, move validation, descendant counts, subtree_ids; (2) the data-sort-mode attribute no longer DB-walks resolve_sort per children <ul> per render — load_tree resolves the root mode once and task_node threads it down (child = own mode || parent's resolved). Indexes were considered and skipped: parent_id/initiative_id are already indexed and the cost was query count, not query cost. Broader data-layer work (load_tree scaling, pagination, index strategy) is parked in PLAN.md Deferred Decisions, triggered by M03 API scoping.
2026-06-09  Fix: inaudible bonk + low-contrast light mode. The no-op-move bonk was a pure sine sweeping 150->70 Hz — below what laptop speakers reproduce (tab showed the speaker icon, nobody heard it); now a triangle wave at 220->110 Hz with more gain. Light mode: task-row borders zinc-300 -> zinc-400 (top accent 400 -> 500) and the drag-handle dots zinc-300 -> zinc-500 (hover 700) — both were too faint. §8 findings.
2026-06-09  Test: Playwright e2e suites for completion confirms, keyboard, and suppression (.03 §8.7.3-6); rig scope settled. Three suites cover the logic-heavy browser checks: completion-flip scenarios 1/2/3 + cancel + second-tab PubSub broadcast (two browser contexts); real keydowns through .TaskKeys (selection arrows, Enter/Space, N/S, P/W/A stepping, Alt+P focus, Del, scroll-into-view, suppression in text fields); confirmation suppression (per class, across reload via localStorage, deletes always confirm) with accept_dialogs: false as a global native-dialog tripwire. The originally planned sort-menu/drag/touch/visual e2e suites were handed back to [Human] passes at the operator's call — e2e is slow by nature (~10s/test) and runs once or twice per arc, never in the dev loop. §8 items 16/18 trimmed to their visual-only remainders. Shared fixtures/flows live in test/support/e2e_helpers.ex.
2026-06-09  Fix: collapsed branches could expand on sort/reorder (§8.11 finding, "sorting expands everything"). Collapse state lives in localStorage and the server never renders collapsed-peek; the per-hook updated() re-apply misses some patch paths (nodes moved optimistically by DragReorder then reconciled by morphdom, replaced subtrees). A document-level MutationObserver now re-applies every collapse state after any class/childList change — no patch path can expand a collapsed branch (classList.toggle with a no-op force doesn't write, so it converges). e2e regression net: collapse survives sorting (unrelated branch, branch inside the sorted one, the sorted branch itself), keyboard reorders around a collapsed branch, and dragging the collapsed branch to a new parent. Side find: the assert_has text: filter is unreliable combined with li:first-child in phoenix_test_playwright — e2e asserts use id-composed CSS instead.
2026-06-10  Spec restoration trio (.03.01.12, .03.07.03, .03.04.03) — built after the operator's sluggishness findings led to spec-level norms (UX_GUARDRAILS 6.3 widened, 6.5 added; ProductSpec Collaboration Model scaling sentence; CLAUDE.md state-locality principle). (1) Confirm modals acknowledge the click: active: pressed styles, phx-disable-with, optimistic dismissal via JS.hide at click time. (2) Client-first selection: the highlight is a client-owned DOM attribute + CSS re-asserted by the guard observer; selected_id left the tree render, so arrow nav no longer re-diffs the tree; the pane load trails rapid nav by 150ms; keyboard events carry the client's selected id (kbd_target/2 guards initiative + can_edit); Enter toggling moved client-side. (3) Incremental tree updates: attribute-level writes and task_updated broadcasts patch the in-memory tree (Tasks.lineage/1 — one recursive CTE — merged by the pure DoIt.Tasks.Tree, parent child-order re-keyed since auto-sorted parents resort on update); structural ops keep full load_tree. Measured at 29 tasks: patch ~41ms vs full reload ~34ms (query count dominates at this size; the point is the slope — O(depth + siblings) vs O(tree), per the new spec line). ancestor_ids also became a CTE (was ~5ms per depth level). All 144 plain tests + 15 e2e green.
2026-06-10  Fix: collaborators never saw a resort (§8.11 finding). Regression from the incremental-tree-updates change: set_sort broadcasts task_updated for the sorted parent, and patch_task re-keyed only the parent's order among its siblings — never the parent's own children, which is what a resort changes. patch_task now re-keys both levels (and refreshes root_sort_mode when the system root's sort changes, so inheriting branches re-resolve). Regression test: a collaborator's set_sort reaches another mounted view's rendered order.
2026-06-10  Fix: Inherit was inert and unlabeled (§8.11 finding, both halves). (1) Picking Inherit never re-ordered children — set_sort resorted only on an explicit non-manual mode, so a branch set to inherit under an Alphabetical ancestor claimed an order the screen didn't show; set_sort now resorts by the RESOLVED mode (explicit modes resolve to themselves, manual stays a no-op). (2) The Inherit option now always names what it means — "Inherit (Alphabetical)", "Inherit (Manual)" when nothing above sets a mode — including when the task currently has an explicit mode (resolution from the parent chain, ignoring the task's own); and the sort select blurs after a pick, since LiveView never patches the focused element and the stale option/label would otherwise linger. §8.11.5 doc line rewritten (it codified the old no-resort behavior). Regression test: inherit under an alphabetical ancestor re-orders immediately.
2026-06-10  Feat/fix trio from §8.11-adjacent findings. (1) The Inherit option folds direction into terse wording — "Inherit (Alphabetical A–Z)", "(highest priority)", "(least complete)" / "(most complete)" (a nod to the open/in_progress/done non-dichotomy), "(oldest 1st)", "(recently updated)" / "(stalest)" — since the Reverse checkbox is disabled on Inherit, the label is where direction lives. (2) Cross-parent moves (drag and keyboard dedent/indent) pink BOTH immediate parents alongside the moved row — one loses a child, one gains, their % moves in almost every case, and the parent rows stay visible even when a destination's children are collapsed (the operator's "destination didn't pink" was dest rows pinking inside a clipped collapsed list). Ancestor chains above stay quiet. (3) "Apply to all descendants" became "Make descendants inherit" (a real button): cascade_sort/2 now clears every descendant branch to inherit — a live link to this branch's setting instead of a stamped copy that drifts — with each level resorting by its resolved mode; broadcasts the structural message so collaborators full-reload (multi-level reorder exceeds the one-level incremental patch); root keeps its explicit setting; confirm modal wording updated.
2026-06-10  Feat: leaf-average roll-up is the default (.03.09.01, ProductSpec § Roll-up Progress rewritten). A branch's progress is the weighted average over ALL descendant leaves — every leaf counts wherever it sits — replacing the first-generation average where each direct child counted as one unit regardless of subtree size (the AbstractSpoon-inspired behavior we should have started with). A leaf's effective weight is the product of weights along its path: weighting an intermediate branch scales its whole subtree on the way up; all-default weights = a plain leaf average. Mechanics: leaf averages aren't derivable level-by-level from persisted child percentages (they need leaf masses), so reconciliation recomputes the initiative's values from one query (Progress.compute_all over the assembled tree, system root included) and writes only diffs — self-healing by construction; Progress.compute_for_branch and the per-level ancestor walk are gone. The Initiative header bar is now the system root's roll-up — same math end to end. First-generation mode returns later as a per-initiative setting (BACKLOG → Initiative settings). Tests: design examples (nested dilution 50→20 and 50→67, flat agreement, path-product weights, compute_all parity incl. zero-weight subtrees); cross-list fixture re-parented under the system root (predated the single-root model). Dev DB reconciled in place.
2026-06-10  Feat: instant Details pane (.03.07.04). Selecting a task opens the pane shell immediately — header + title prefilled from the row (data-task-title), remaining fields as a pulse skeleton — and the server render replaces it (the real pane carries data-task-id; the client hides the skeleton when they match). Transient with a 3s guard timeout; closing via the pane's X / mobile backdrop / switching to the initiative editor clears the client selection so highlight and skeleton can't outlive the pane. Mobile's flyout keeps server timing (overlay layout classes are server-keyed).
2026-06-11  Feat: "Progress" merged into "Completion %" (.03.02.05). Two near-identical sort entries (status buckets vs the visible percentage) became one: Completion %, backed by the roll-up percentage users see on every underbar. Natural direction = least complete first ("least complete" / "most complete" labels unchanged); done sorts as 100 by construction. The status-bucket comparator is gone — its only extra, distinguishing in_progress, is unreachable from the current UI; the unknown-mode fallback keeps any straggler data harmless and a bucket mode can return cheaply if in_progress ever becomes real. Migration repoints stored computed_progress modes to completion. (Process note: the generated migration file was container-owned; the first host-side write silently failed and the EMPTY migration ran — caught via cat + ecto.migrations, rolled back, rewritten through the container, re-run. Watch for that failure mode with generated files.)
2026-06-11  Feat: the Initiative pane doubles as the Settings panel (.03.07.05). The initiative editor gains a second headed section, Settings, holding initiative-wide behavior — "Sort lists by" moved in, (admin) Delete as the danger tail — and giving the parked per-initiative settings (progress calc mode, BACKLOG → Initiative settings) their home.
2026-06-11  Fix: the instant pane shell shows the real UI, not placeholder rectangles (.03.07.04 redone per operator). The shell mirrors the task editor's form: title / priority / weight / assignee prefill live from the row's pills (values already in the DOM need no loading state); description, comments, and activity — the genuinely server-only parts — render as disabled "Loading…" sections. Same swap mechanics as before (server pane replaces the shell; 3s guard).
2026-06-11  Rework: one pane, never swapped (.03.07.06) + collapsed Initiative Settings with the progress-calc toggle (.03.07.07, .03.09.02). The shell/real pane pair was UI jerk-around (operator): the swap broke focus and visual continuity exactly when the user wanted to act. Now the real pane stays mounted once created — deselecting hides it (selected_task keeps the last pane data; only selected_task_id nils), a selection switch client-writes the row-known values into the real fields (skipping the focused element) and dims the [data-pane-async] comments/activity sections, and the server patch reconciles the same elements in place; in-progress typing survives because LiveView never patches the focused field. Only a page visit's first-ever selection still waits for the server. Initiative pane: "Sort lists by" returns to the details body; Settings is a native <details>, collapsed by default (KeepOpen hook preserves its state across patches), holding the new per-initiative progress calculation selector — leaf average (default) vs first-generation children (initiatives.progress_calc, validated, migration). Switching recomputes the whole initiative under the new mode (Progress.compute/2 + compute_all/2 carry both) and broadcasts a full-reload (Tasks.notify_tree_changed/2). Mount now assigns the pane defaults (selected_task/comments/activity) since the pane persists.
2026-06-11  Fix: pane layout shift + initiative editor lag (§-finding, UX_GUARDRAILS 1.1/6.5). The branch-only copy under the progress slider and the sort menu now keep their space when not applicable (invisible, not removed) — leaf↔branch selection switches stop jolting the layout; the leaf/branch progress blocks merged into one always-rendered block (single slider, disabled for branches). The initiative editor became persistent like the task pane: always rendered reading @root_task (load_tree attaches the top-level tasks as its children so leaf? costs no query; patch_task keeps it fresh), hidden toggled server-side and flipped client-instantly on the title click / close controls. Sort controls (set_sort form, cascade button) carry their own task id, decoupling them from the task selection — edit_initiative no longer hijacks selected_task (which also fixed a duplicate sort-form id between the two panes). The Settings calc selector gains a "?" info hint explaining leaf average vs first-generation.
2026-06-11  Fix: zero-jank pane second pass (operator findings). (1) scrollbar-gutter: stable on the pane container — no more sideways reflow when the scrollbar appears/disappears. (2) Sort UI joins the client-instant fields: task <li>s carry data-sort / data-sort-reverse (the task's OWN mode), the in-flight fill toggles the sort block's visibility from children-presence and sets select + Reverse (incl. its disabled state); the Inherit parenthetical corrects text-only on the patch. (3) Comments + activity show an explicit "Loading…" during a switch instead of the previous task's data dimmed; the add-comment form stays live for power users — select_task precedes any submit in the LiveView event queue, so an instant comment lands on the right task. (4) info_hint rebuilt on the native Popover API: the panel renders in the browser top layer (no more clipping/scrollbars inside the overflow-y pane), positioned next to its trigger and clamped to the viewport by a small Popover hook; light dismiss is native.
2026-06-11  Rename: "First-generation children" -> "Single-level average" (operator naming; "level" is the lay word where "depth"/"generation" carry jargon, and it parallels "Leaf average"). Full rename, not label-only: UI select + explainer, ProductSpec prose, Progress mode atom :single_level, initiatives.progress_calc values via migration (down restores), internal fn names, tests, arc-doc mentions. Same session: ProductSpec's Visual Metaphor rule relaxed from "icon layer only" to a principle — formal names stay plain, but examples may speak the metaphor and metaphor terms may serve where plain vocabulary has no analog; "Leaf task" enters the Vocabulary under that rule; Fruit/Crop stay reserved.
2026-06-11  Fix: pane labels gained their for attributes (operator finding; UX_GUARDRAILS 4.1). Subtitle, Title, Description, Manual progress, Priority, Weight, Assignee — each label now points at its control (description / subtitle / progress controls minted ids). The "Don't show this again" confirm label was already valid (it wraps its checkbox); the sort and calc selects already had theirs.
2026-06-11  Fix: indirect resorts now reach simultaneous collaborators (operator principle-check: "aren't simcolls supposed to know about reorgs?"). The incremental patch re-keyed only two levels (the written task's siblings + its own children), but progress-keyed sort modes resort ANCESTOR levels when a descendant's roll-up changes — those reorders landed in the DB and reached nobody's screen (not even the actor's) until a full reload. patched_tree now re-keys every lineage level's child order in one query (ordered_child_ids_by_parent/1). Regression test: completing a deep leaf re-sorts a completion-%-keyed grandparent level in a mounted view.
2026-06-11  Fix: collaboration was broadly broken — broadcasts fired MID-TRANSACTION (operator: "No CollabyWabby"). Subscribers received the message instantly, reloaded the tree, and read the database before the commit landed — re-rendering the OLD state with nothing to tell them again. Real Postgres hides uncommitted writes across connections; the test sandbox shares one, so every regression test (and even the two-tab e2e) passed while real windows stayed stale — false confidence, named as such. broadcast_change now queues inside a transaction; flush_broadcasts/1 sends the queue at the outermost mutator's exit (with_resort_batching + set_sort), only on success; previews discard their dry-run queue. Tests pin the mechanics the sandbox can see: success broadcasts, failures and previews never do.
2026-06-11  Fix: the last view-state server round-trips are gone (operator: "I wanna type the name of a task before I add it" — UX_GUARDRAILS 6.5 sweep). Opening any add-task form (New List / New Subtask / Add Sibling / keyboard N and S) and Cancel each cost a round trip; so did the Add Member form. Now one global add-task form lives in a phx-update="ignore" home and is client-teleported into per-row ignored slots — typing starts the instant the button/key is pressed, and no LiveView patch can disturb the form mid-entry. create_task reads parent_id/after_id hidden inputs the client sets (new_task_position and the add_task_for/add_task_after assigns are gone); submitting clears the title and keeps focus, so consecutive adds need zero clicks. Add Member became a client-toggled <details> with KeepOpen. Removed events: show_add_root/child/sibling, cancel_add, kbd_new_subtask/sibling, show_member_form, cancel_member. e2e helper hardened: selection sync now also waits for the pane (client-instant highlight had outpaced pane-dependent steps).
2026-06-11  Feat: optimistic row echo + leaf-count badge + optimistic checkbox (.03.07.11-13, operator directives). (11) Pane field edits write the selected row at the keystroke — title, description (row line now always in the DOM, hidden when empty), priority/weight/assignee pills, and a leaf's progress bar + the pane's % readout; pills moved their default-vs-set styling onto a data-pill-set attribute (Tailwind data-variants) so the echo is one attribute flip, and the server patch re-renders the same values. Roll-up math is never predicted (saving hue covers it). (12) The collapse chevron's "(N)" now counts the subtree's leaf tasks, not direct children. (13) The leaf completion checkbox flips optimistically: its styling keys off aria-pressed (check icon included via group-aria-pressed), the click handler flips the attribute; branch cascades stay server-timed; leaf toggles commit directly (no confirm class covers them), so nothing can intercept the flip. From §8.18.1's recorded judgment ("wants optimism for sure"); §8.18.3 added for the human re-check.
2026-06-11  Fix: confirms preserve optimism (.03.07.14, UX_GUARDRAILS 6.6 — operator finding in §8.20: "confirmations must not undo the optimistic state"). A drag that raised a completion-flip confirm deliberately snapped the row back (reply committed: false) while the modal opened. Now the optimistic placement holds while the user decides: the client parks a revert handle (window.DoitPendingMove), the pending-hue render patches classes only (server order unchanged) so the row stays put, and the server announces the outcome via push_event — "confirm-cancelled" (cancel_pending, or a failed Proceed commit) reverts the row home; "confirm-resolved" (confirm_pending closed) releases the handle to the commit's re-render. Guardrail added as 6.6. LiveView tests assert both events.
2026-06-11  Fix: client-instant delete confirm (.03.07.15 — operator finding: deletion was "too slow before the confirm"; an earlier sweep had wrongly classified ALL confirm flows as legitimate server hits, lumping the dialog's OPEN — pure view state — with its DECISION). Task deletion's dialog content (title + irreversibility copy) is fully client-known, so it's now a client-rendered modal (#delete-confirm, phx-update="ignore"): opens at Del/click with the title filled from the row, sticky maybe-write hue on the doomed subtree (markSaving gained a sticky option — no 1.5s safety fade while a dialog holds it), Cancel/Escape/backdrop close free, Delete pushes the new delete_task event alongside the existing optimistic row removal. request_delete_task and the :delete_task pending plumbing (confirm body/title, pending ids, data-optimistic-remove) are removed; reading the target from the client selection also fixes a latent race where an in-flight pane switch could delete the previously selected task. UX_GUARDRAILS 6.5 now names the case. Initiative delete still round-trips (flagged in the arc item as the sibling candidate). e2e delete flows repointed at #delete-confirm.
2026-06-11  Fix: Cancel on server confirms is client-instant (.03.07.16 — operator: "the user can't hop to their next ui action seamlessly without waiting"; the agent had wrongly claimed "nothing waits on it" while the held drag's revert and the unpinking both rode the cancel_pending round trip). The Cancel button (data-confirm-cancel) and backdrop click now revert the held placement and strip the is-saving hue at the click; cancel_pending reconciles the same state behind it, and the "confirm-cancelled" push event remains as the backstop for failed Proceed commits. Process change, same exchange: NOBODY runs the Playwright e2e suite anymore — the operator tests in-browser directly (10x faster than the rig); anything needing browser verification becomes a [Human] action item in the arc's testing section. The e2e suite stays parked in the repo, excluded by default.
2026-06-11  Removed: the Playwright e2e rig, in full (operator: "delete the e2e suite, we're done with it, it was a way dumber idea than I thought"). Deleted test/e2e/ (smoke, completion-confirm, keyboard, suppression, collapse-persistence), test/support/e2e_helpers.ex, the phoenix_test_playwright + websockex deps (lock pruned: phoenix_test, playwright_ex, nimble_options too), the mix test.e2e alias + env shim, the playwright compose service (running container removed), the test_helper.exs gating (back to two lines), and the e2e README section. config/test.exs endpoint reverted to loopback/server: false — the 0.0.0.0 listener existed only for the browser container. §8.7 struck with a retirement note. Browser verification is [Human] action items in the arc testing sections from here on; plain mix test (143 tests) is the only automated gate.
2026-06-11  Fix: the round-trip audit, actually done this time (.03.07.17-20 — operator: "ROUND TRIPS THAT HALT THE UX WHEN WE HAVE THE INFO CLIENT SIDE OR ARE PURELY UI ANYWAY NEED TO GO TO HELL"; every server event in both LiveViews inventoried and classified). Killed: (17) field-focus round trips — Alt+P/W/A and pill taps focused a pane field via kbd_focus_field / a focus param on select_task; both focus client-side now (pills carry data-pill; first-ever selection parks the focus in DoitPendingFocus until the pane arrives; kbd_focus_field, push_focus, and the FocusField hook deleted). (18) request_delete_initiative — dialog content is known at render; now a client modal like the task one (#delete-initiative-confirm, name baked in; Proceed pushes delete_initiative). The last :delete_* pending kinds are gone, so the server confirm modal's destructive styling paths are deleted too. (19) The initiatives index: show_new/cancel_new gated typing an initiative name — now a client <details> + KeepOpen (create pushes close-details to close + reset; errors leave it open); sort-control changes re-streamed server-side to reorder rows whose keys the client can see — cards carry data-name/-progress/-created/-updated and explicit modes reorder client-side at the change ("Recent" stays server-derived). (20) The mobile flyout was server-keyed (.03.07.04's known remainder) — the rail's overlay/sticky/hidden classes now hang off ONE data-open attribute (Tailwind data-variants) the client flips at the tap; backdrop always rendered, hidden toggled (syncRail in the selection/pane sync). Remaining server hits after the audit are all data: pane loads, writes, the flip-preview confirms, and their Proceed decisions. §8.26 [Human] round-trip-audit pass added (walkthrough renumbered 27).
2026-06-11  Doc: §8.27 stress walkthrough redrafted as the Interleaving pass (operator challenged the redundancy; the dev DB profile — 28 tasks at depth 19, sort modes mixed manual/alphabetical/completion, done/open mix — shows scale and mixed-mode verification already happened organically, contradicting the agent's assumption that it hadn't). What remains genuinely untested is operations colliding mid-flight; redrafted to five concrete collision recipes with the agent as second actor via timed domain-layer writes (real PubSub broadcasts), so no human helper is needed.
2026-06-11  Doc + test: §8.20 rewritten stepwise (operator: "written inconcise and very difficult to understand" — the old subitems packed two scenarios per line and specified by mechanism instead of by what the eye sees). New form: setup sentence, then one observation per line in execution order. Process change, same exchange: a failed [Human] set is reported AS a set ("8.20 fails"), and the agent owns the diagnosis — no per-subitem specification expected from the operator. Server side of the full cycle (flip-confirm → cancel → identical redo → proceed) pinned by a new LiveView test; generated CSS verified to contain all the data-variant rules the client-instant work leans on.
2026-06-11  Fix: §8.20.1 failure — the dragged row "snapped back when the modal opened" (operator set-level report). Root cause: while the row is held away from its server-side parent, the confirm's pending-hue patch reconciles the OLD parent's child list against the server's expected contents and re-creates the row there as a CLONE — the original was still at the held spot (which is why the deleted e2e's one-sided assert passed), but the clone appearing under the source branch is exactly the visible snap-back. Two fixes: the hold handle is now registered synchronously at the drop (before any patch or reply can race it; the reply callback releases it on commit, reverts on failure, keeps it for committed: false), and every hold assert/release pass kills same-id clones (removePendingMoveClones, run from applyPendingMove, revertPendingMove, and the guard observer passes they ride). Operator re-runs §8.20 to confirm.
2026-06-11  Doc: §8 gains a saving-hue judging note (operator, after §8.21.3: "questioning whether any flashes are happening including ones I've checked off already" — they're right to question). The optimistic hue is real but on a local stack the write confirms in tens of milliseconds, so the client-added is-saving class is stripped by the patch within a frame or two — below perception. This is consistent with UX_GUARDRAILS 6.1 (progress indicators are for operations longer than ~100ms); the hue earns its keep on slow networks, large cascades, and the server-held maybe-write pinks (which do persist and are what the operator has actually been seeing). Verification method documented: liveSocket.enableLatencySim(500) in the console makes every flash plainly visible for scope judgments. Earlier flash check-offs stand as scope checks the operator may optionally re-spot-check under latency sim. (Also fixed a [X%] checkbox typo on §8.20.)
2026-06-11  Fix: manual-progress writes now pink row + ancestors (.03.07.21, operator finding in §8.18.3 under latency sim — the slider was absent from the saving-hue wiring, so a progress write showed no in-flight signal anywhere while ancestors recomputed). Rolls up like weight. Ancestor roll-up VALUES deliberately stay server-computed — see arc item for the duplication argument.
2026-06-11  Feat: fully-optimistic operated row (.03.07.22 — operator: "few things are more annoying than wondering whether a checkbox is working"; scope deliberately the operated row only, ancestor roll-up values stay server-computed per .03.07.21's duplication argument). Every completion toggle — leaf AND branch — now flips the clicked row at the click: aria-pressed, done styling (data-done on the row drives strikethrough + bar color via group-data variants, replacing the server-conditional classes), and the row's progress bar (done → 100; reopened leaf restores its dormant manual value from a new data-manual-progress attr, kept fresh by the slider echo; reopened branch waits for the recompute). Branch toggles moved from phx-click to a DoitPush with a reply (DoitPush now forwards callbacks); toggle_complete/request_cascade reply with the move_task contract — ok: false reverts, committed: true releases, committed: false holds the flip through the cascade confirm via the guard net (DoitPendingToggle, sibling of DoitPendingMove): Cancel/click-away/failed-Proceed revert (commit_cascade failures push confirm-cancelled), Proceed keeps it. §8.26 grew checks 6-8 and now spans .17-22.
2026-06-11  Fix: confirm-modal Proceed appeared to unpink instead of holding the hue through the write (operator finding under latency sim). Root cause: the CLIENT pink from the original click (toggle / drag gesture) carries a 1.5s safety timer; once the confirm modal opened, the server's pending_saving_ids rendered the same is-saving class on the same rows — and the timer then stripped it mid-decision, so by Proceed-time the hue was already gone. Fix: hand the hue to the server when a confirm takes over — releaseSavingHue() (and DragReorder's releaseSaving()) stop tracking WITHOUT stripping classes; the guard observer disarms the timer whenever #completion-confirm is present, and the drag reply's committed:false path releases instead of clearing. Cancel still strips instantly (.03.07.16); Proceed now holds pink until the commit patch lands.
2026-06-11  Perf: test suite 70s -> 48s — config/test.exs was missing `config :bcrypt_elixir, :log_rounds, 1`, so nearly every test paid full-cost password hashing in register_and_log_in. Workflow note (operator: "lots of docker commands… getting worse"): the docker exec wrapper costs milliseconds; the felt cost was full-suite runs on every small change + the bcrypt tax. Loop discipline recorded: targeted test files per change, full suite once pre-commit.
2026-06-11  Fix + feat: uncheck optimism + indeterminate "recomputing" bars (.03.07.23). Bug (operator: "Unchecking gets no progress optimism"): .22's bar restore read data-manual-progress, but checking had just SET manual to 100 (maybe_set_done_progress snaps 100 on →done, 0 on done→open — cascades explicitly included), so the "restore" was a no-op and the operator's "obviously 100% or 0%" was simply correct — the agent's dormant-value pushback didn't apply to toggles. Every toggle outcome is now optimistic both directions, leaf and branch (done→100, reopened→0); data-manual-progress removed. Design (operator proposal, refined together: gradient instead of gray-50): rows whose % genuinely is in flight — ancestors of progress-affecting writes (toggle/cascade/weight/slider/reparent/cross-parent drag), cascade descendants, confirm-held flip rows — get is-recomputing: the bar becomes a full-width left→right fade from emerald into the track color (no fill-edge to misread; dark mode free via transparency), pulses slowly, and shows "…" instead of a number (CSS-only ::after swap, patch-proof). Never the operated row. Client class rides the pink lifecycle (markRecomputing / cleared together / morphdom-stripped); the held-modal era renders it server-side (pending_recompute_ids = pending_saving_ids minus the operated task; cascade-sort confirms excluded — no % moves). LiveView test pins the held-era rendering; §8.26.9 added for the eye.
2026-06-11  Spec draft: remove Weight from the product (operator, after checking the TDL inspiration: no weight attribute there — they recall deliberately decomposing important branches into more leaves so they'd weigh more, "which works really well in practice: more important branches get more detail; nobody's mad"). Agent concurred: leaf-average roll-up (m02.03.09) already made subtree leaf-count the natural weight, weight is the most explanation-hungry feature (it headlines the info_hint list), weight-sort was built-but-never-surfaced, and m03-api doesn't mention it yet — so pre-API is the cheap moment. ProductSpec revised (Core Idea, Vocabulary, Durable Principles — new principle "Importance is expressed by decomposition, not configuration" — Roll-up formula now sum(leaf_progress)/leaf_count, sort criteria); arc doc gains §10 Weight removal (7 items: math, UI surfaces, sort engine, schema drop, doc sweep, tests, [Human] eye-check). Both draft-marked, pending operator approval; no code touched.
